<br>
Well maybe you wouldn't be so ignorant. I think your smug post, with your pompous all white school, and the narcissistic praise of your own academic acheivements makes my point.<br>
<br>
But the true answer to your question, is that it does a lot for the learning process, in fact it is very important. You are small minded if you think that education is only about book learning. All colleges seek to educate and develop the mind and the soul. Learning about yourself and the world around you is just as important, and goes hand in hand, with your academic learning. How can someone expect to become a truly engaged individual in the diverse world we live in, without having any interaction in a diverse setting? As you have shown, the result is becoming defensive, and criticizing the system, calling it unfair. <br>
<br>
When in fact, the system in place seeks to make the system MORE fair. I'll give an example that unfortunately is way too common in inner city public education. You have a minority, who does really well in school, let's say top 10% of the class. But, the school is in a poor neighborhood, this means less taxes, which means less money available to the school, which means a lesser quality education. What usually goes hand in hand in this situation is a lack of SAT preparation. So, this student, who does great in school, has dreams of going to college, tests poorly on the SAT. For this student, this precludes them from being admitted to just about any half-decent college out there. But, it is not really the student's fault. They have the intelligence needed to succeed in post secondary education, yet will be forced to follow that dream at a community college or state school. So, what happens if that rich white kid happens to lose his spot to this minority (which by the way is not how most colleges work-because a minority with lower credentials is admitted does NOT mean one deserving student is then rejected-I'm just using the scenario that most think is how it works)? Well, what a shame, I guess it's off to Princeton instead of Harvard for poor Todd, whereas the minority doens't really have any other options. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=639407" target="top">Kozul Goodheart</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
