Close, not exactly, people arent looked at as numbers. Now, I am at a private university, no funding whatsoever, so I can speak for private universities. With state schools, yes they have funding, but again, the people are NOT looked at as numbers. I am a college admissions counselor, I would know. Until you work in the university environment such as me, you have no idea what you are talking about. When I come across the application of a minority, from a bad neighborhood, who has done well in school, but has low SAT, I bring the app to the dean, and we go over it. Usually, what happens is we agree that this person has come so far from so little, who are we to crush their dreams of going to college. We give them a chance. We feel their experiences would be a nice thing to share with the others. We dont get a cent from it, in fact, it detracts from our statistics such as average SAT, and other numbers that are used to determine rank and such. So, yes, we do it for the reason I listed before.<br>
